│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs in TreeEntry::getOperand(unsigned OpIdx) with OpIdx =        │
│ 4294967295 (UINT_MAX). This happens during cost computation in                │
│ BoUpSLP::getEntryCost(). The assertion OpIdx < Operands.size() rightfully     │
│ fires because UINT_MAX is a sentinel value used in EdgeInfo (EdgeIdx default) │
│ to indicate 'no valid operand index'. Passing it to getOperand is therefore   │
│ invalid. The assertion is correct; earlier logic should have prevented using  │
│ such an EdgeIdx.                                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The log shows successful tree construction and scheduling for several bundles │
│ (shl/or/select/icmp chains). Costing proceeds until it hits the assertion     │
│ while calculating costs for the tree ("Calculated costs for Tree" line        │
│ printed just before crashing). The failing path is inside the GetCostDiff     │
│ lambda in getEntryCost(). This code attempts to adjust vectorization cost     │
│ based on the parent/user node's operand types (minimum bit-width resizing     │
│ logic). It blindly indexes EI.UserTE->getOperand(EI.EdgeIdx) assuming EdgeIdx │
│ is valid. For some gather/scalar reuse patterns (like trivial zero chains in  │
│ the reproducer), an EdgeInfo with EdgeIdx == UINT_MAX is stored. This matches │
│ existing uses elsewhere (e.g. special-casing gather nodes in                  │
│ getGatherShuffledSingleRegisterEntry()).                                      │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ EdgeInfo::EdgeIdx == UINT_MAX denotes an edge without a specific operand      │
│ position (e.g. synthetic/gather or special external user relationship). In    │
│ getEntryCost(), the resizing logic:                                           │
│   const EdgeInfo &EI = E->UserTreeIndices.front();                            │
│   Type *UserScalarTy = EI.UserTE->getOperand(EI.EdgeIdx).front()->getType();  │
│ executes unconditionally once prior guards pass, without verifying EI.EdgeIdx │
│ != UINT_MAX. When EI.EdgeIdx == UINT_MAX, this invokes                        │
│ TreeEntry::getOperand(UINT_MAX), triggering the assertion. The reproducer     │
│ creates a degenerate chain where a node with MinBWs entry and a user recorded │
│ via EdgeInfo lacks a concrete operand index, exposing the bug.                │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Add a guard in BoUpSLP::getEntryCost() before dereferencing EI.EdgeIdx. Only  │
│ attempt the user operand type adjustment if EI.EdgeIdx is a valid operand     │
│ index (i.e., EI.EdgeIdx != UINT_MAX and EI.UserTE is non-null). This prevents │
│ passing UINT_MAX to getOperand(). Also incorporate the guard into the         │
│ existing if-condition to avoid unnecessary nesting. Provide a clarifying      │
│ comment explaining why UINT_MAX must be skipped.                              │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit lines 10343-10356 (within getEntryCost):                                 │
│ Original snippet logic:                                                       │
│   const EdgeInfo &EI = E->UserTreeIndices.front();                            │
│   if ((EI.UserTE->getOpcode() != Instruction::Select || EI.EdgeIdx != 0) &&   │
│ It != MinBWs.end()) {                                                         │
│     auto UserBWIt = MinBWs.find(EI.UserTE);                                   │
│     Type *UserScalarTy =                                                      │
│ EI.UserTE->getOperand(EI.EdgeIdx).front()->getType();                         │
│     ...                                                                       │
│ Replace with guarded version:                                                 │
│   const EdgeInfo &EI = E->UserTreeIndices.front();                            │
│   // EdgeIdx may be UINT_MAX for synthetic/gather relationships; skip         │
│ resizing logic in that case.                                                  │
│   if (EI.EdgeIdx != UINT_MAX &&                                               │
│       (EI.UserTE->getOpcode() != Instruction::Select || EI.EdgeIdx != 0) &&   │
│       It != MinBWs.end()) {                                                   │
│     auto UserBWIt = MinBWs.find(EI.UserTE);                                   │
│     Type *UserScalarTy =                                                      │
│ EI.UserTE->getOperand(EI.EdgeIdx).front()->getType();                         │
│     ...                                                                       │
│ This prevents invalid operand access. No other semantic changes are needed.   │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The fix adds a necessary guard against using a sentinel EdgeIdx (UINT_MAX) as │
│ an operand index during cost estimation. This preserves the assertion's       │
│ integrity and prevents crashes for trees containing gather/special edges. The │
│ expected effect is that the reproducer no longer aborts, and costing proceeds │
│ normally (possibly skipping the resizing adjustment for such nodes). This     │
│ aligns with existing patterns handling EdgeIdx == UINT_MAX elsewhere in the   │
│ SLP vectorizer.                                                               │
│                                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
