  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in
TreeEntry::getOperand(unsigned OpIdx) with OpIdx = 4294967295 (UINT_MAX). This
happens during cost computation in BoUpSLP::getEntryCost(). The assertion OpIdx <
Operands.size() rightfully fires because UINT_MAX is a sentinel value used in
EdgeInfo (EdgeIdx default) to indicate 'no valid operand index'. Passing it to
getOperand is therefore invalid. The assertion is correct; earlier logic should
have prevented using such an EdgeIdx.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log shows
successful tree construction and scheduling for several bundles
(shl/or/select/icmp chains). Costing proceeds until it hits the assertion while
calculating costs for the tree (\"Calculated costs for Tree\" line printed just
before crashing). The failing path is inside the GetCostDiff lambda in
getEntryCost(). This code attempts to adjust vectorization cost based on the
parent/user node's operand types (minimum bit-width resizing logic). It blindly
indexes EI.UserTE->getOperand(EI.EdgeIdx) assuming EdgeIdx is valid. For some
gather/scalar reuse patterns (like trivial zero chains in the reproducer), an
EdgeInfo with EdgeIdx == UINT_MAX is stored. This matches existing uses elsewhere
(e.g. special-casing gather nodes in
getGatherShuffledSingleRegisterEntry()).\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nEdgeInfo::EdgeIdx == UINT_MAX denotes an edge without a specific
operand position (e.g. synthetic/gather or special external user relationship).
In getEntryCost(), the resizing logic:\n  const EdgeInfo &EI =
E->UserTreeIndices.front();\n  Type *UserScalarTy =
EI.UserTE->getOperand(EI.EdgeIdx).front()->getType();\nexecutes unconditionally
once prior guards pass, without verifying EI.EdgeIdx != UINT_MAX. When EI.EdgeIdx
== UINT_MAX, this invokes TreeEntry::getOperand(UINT_MAX), triggering the
assertion. The reproducer creates a degenerate chain where a node with MinBWs
entry and a user recorded via EdgeInfo lacks a concrete operand index, exposing
the bug.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nAdd a guard in BoUpSLP::getEntryCost()
before dereferencing EI.EdgeIdx. Only attempt the user operand type adjustment if
EI.EdgeIdx is a valid operand index (i.e., EI.EdgeIdx != UINT_MAX and EI.UserTE
is non-null). This prevents passing UINT_MAX to getOperand(). Also incorporate
the guard into the existing if-condition to avoid unnecessary nesting. Provide a
clarifying comment explaining why UINT_MAX must be skipped.\n\nEdit lines
10343-10356 (within getEntryCost):\nOriginal snippet logic:\n  const EdgeInfo &EI
= E->UserTreeIndices.front();\n  if ((EI.UserTE->getOpcode() !=
Instruction::Select || EI.EdgeIdx != 0) && It != MinBWs.end()) {\n    auto
UserBWIt = MinBWs.find(EI.UserTE);\n    Type *UserScalarTy =
EI.UserTE->getOperand(EI.EdgeIdx).front()->getType();\n    ...\nReplace with
guarded version:\n  const EdgeInfo &EI = E->UserTreeIndices.front();\n  //
EdgeIdx may be UINT_MAX for synthetic/gather relationships; skip resizing logic
in that case.\n  if (EI.EdgeIdx != UINT_MAX &&\n      (EI.UserTE->getOpcode() !=
Instruction::Select || EI.EdgeIdx != 0) &&\n      It != MinBWs.end()) {\n    auto
UserBWIt = MinBWs.find(EI.UserTE);\n    Type *UserScalarTy =
EI.UserTE->getOperand(EI.EdgeIdx).front()->getType();\n    ...\nThis prevents
invalid operand access. No other semantic changes are needed.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nThe fix adds a necessary guard against using a sentinel EdgeIdx
(UINT_MAX) as an operand index during cost estimation. This preserves the
assertion's integrity and prevents crashes for trees containing gather/special
edges. The expected effect is that the reproducer no longer aborts, and costing
proceeds normally (possibly skipping the resizing adjustment for such nodes).
This aligns with existing patterns handling EdgeIdx == UINT_MAX elsewhere in the
SLP vectorizer.\n",
